name: image_handling_skill
description: Comprehensive image processing and formatting for fault diagnosis workflows, including proper figure structure, annotation details, and source verification for inclusion of technical diagrams and visual aids

triggers:
  - Querying about diagnostic flow charts, troubleshooting diagrams, or schematics
  - Need to display component locations, measurement procedures, or technical drawings
  - Presenting step-by-step repair procedures with visual aids
  - Including equipment schematics or system diagrams in responses

# Image Handling and Inclusion Rules

## Core Principle
All images returned from queries MUST be rendered using proper figure structure with comprehensive annotations and citation sources to support fault diagnosis and troubleshooting.

## Mandatory Image Inclusion Rules

### 1. Figure Structure Format
**Every image MUST be formatted using the proper HTML5 <figure> tag:**

```html
<figure>
    <img src="%image_url%" title="%image_title%"/>
    <figcaption>
        <p>%figure_number%: %figure_name%</p>
        <p>%detailed_purpose_description%</p>
        <p>%annotation_detail%</p>
        <p>%citation_source%</p>
    </figcaption>
</figure>
```

### 2. Figure Element Requirements

#### Figure Name and Number
- **figure_name**: Descriptive name of the image (e.g., "Hydraulic System Schematic", "Bearing Assembly Diagram")
- **figure_number**: Reference number from source or sequential number for documentation purposes

#### Detailed Purpose Description
- **Detailed purpose**: Explain what the image shows visually
- **Text/step correspondence**: Which specific text sections or steps it corresponds to
- **Diagnostic/repair utility**: How it aids in diagnosis, troubleshooting, or repair
- **Technical specifications**: Any standard values or specifications displayed in the image

#### Annotation Detail
**CRITICAL**: Must include ALL details from the sources:
- Figure caption or title from the original document
- Legend explaining symbols, colors, or line types
- Labels and annotations on the diagram
- Component identifiers and part numbers
- Measurement units and scales
- Any notes or warnings associated with the image

#### Citation Source
- Source document title and identifier
- Page number or section reference
- Year or version of the source
- URL or DOI if available
- Follow the verification protocols for source accuracy

### 3. Image Type Prioritization
**Prioritize images that show:**
- **Diagnostic flow charts** and troubleshooting diagrams
- **Component location** and identification (part numbers, positions)
- **Measurement procedures** and standard values
- **Technical specifications** and schematics (electrical, hydraulic, mechanical)
- **Step-by-step repair procedures** with visual guidance

## Image Processing Rules

### Critical Processing Requirements

#### 1. Format Every Image Properly
- **FORMAL REQUIREMENT**: Format every image with valid HTML5 <figure> tag
- **Complete structure**: Include all required elements (img, figcaption, p tags)
- **Proper nesting**: Ensure correct HTML nesting and closing tags
- **Accessibility**: Provide meaningful alt text and title attributes

#### 2. NEVER Fabricate or Hallucinate Image References
- **Prohibited**: If no image is provided in the conversation, do NOT include any <figure> tags
- **Verification**: Confirm image URLs are real and accessible
- **Accuracy**: Do not create imaginary figure numbers or names
- **Source verification**: Ensure images exist in the specified source

#### 3. Provide Detailed Purpose Descriptions
For each image, explain:

**What it shows visually:**
- System components and their relationships
- Measurement points and test locations
- Assembly or disassembly sequences
- Failure modes and symptom indicators

**Text/step correspondence:**
- Which troubleshooting step this supports
- Which section of the diagnosis plan it illustrates
- Which procedure or SOP it relates to

**Technical specifications displayed:**
- Standard values (pressures, temperatures, voltages)
- Tolerance ranges and acceptable limits
- Component specifications (sizes, capacities, ratings)
- Measurement requirements and accuracy

## Source Whitelist (MANDATORY)

### ALLOWED Sources Only
- ✅ **Tool call results**: search_tool, kb_query, db_fetch, and other verified retrieval tools
- ✅ **User-provided content**: Links and uploads in the current conversation context
- ✅ **System resource paths**: Verified paths like /resources/{resource_id}
- ✅ **Verified repository files**: Files stored in the project repository

### PROHIBITED Sources (Never Use)
- ❌ **Training data memory**: "usually...", "typically...", or general patterns from training
- ❌ **Unverified external URLs**: Links not explicitly provided or verified
- ❌ **Hypothetical references**: Imagined or hypothetical image locations
- ❌ **General descriptions**: Descriptions without actual image backing

## Image Content Requirements by Use Case

### Diagnostic Flowcharts
**Required elements:**
- Decision points with clear logic paths
- Symptom-to-cause mapping
- Measurement steps with expected values
- Go/no-go checkpoints
- Safety warnings and critical steps

**Annotation requirements:**
- Decision criteria for each branch
- Expected measurement ranges
- Reference to test procedures
- Component identification (part numbers)
- Source of the flowchart (manual, SOP, etc.)

### Component Location Diagrams
**Required elements:**
- Clear component labeling
- Position references (front/left/top, etc.)
- Adjacent components for context
- Access paths and clearances
- Tools required for access

**Annotation requirements:**
- Part numbers and component names
- Assembly/disassembly sequences
- Replacement warnings (torque specs, sequencing)
- Safety notes (disconnect power, depressurize, etc.)
- Reference to service manual sections

### Measurement Procedure Diagrams
**Required elements:**
- Measurement point locations
- Test equipment setup
- Required tools and gauges
- Standard value ranges
- Acceptable vs. unacceptable indications

**Annotation requirements:**
- Measurement method details
- Procedure steps numbering
- Setup requirements (environment, conditions)
- Data recording format
- Pass/fail criteria

### Technical Specifications and Schematics
**Required elements:**
- Complete circuit/hydraulic/mechanical system depiction
- Component symbols and values
- Connection points and routing
- Ratings and capacities
- Reference designators

**Annotation requirements:**
- Symbol legend
- Component part numbers
- Voltage/current/pressure ratings
- Wire sizes, pipe diameters, or dimensions
- Reference to specification documents

### Step-by-Step Repair Procedures
**Required elements:**
- Sequential visual steps
- Tools required at each step
- Safety precautions per step
- Critical torque or adjustment values
- Quality checkpoints

**Annotation requirements:**
- Step numbers and descriptions
- Hazards and warnings
- Special tool requirements
- Measurement checkpoints
- Completed step appearance

## Application Examples

### Example 1: Diagnostic Flowchart
```html
<figure>
    <img src="/resources/fault-guides/hydraulic-pump-flowchart.png"
         title="Hydraulic Pump Troubleshooting Flowchart"/>
    <figcaption>
        <p>Figure 1: Hydraulic Pump Diagnostic Flowchart</p>
        <p>This flowchart provides systematic troubleshooting guidance for Caterpillar 320
        excavator hydraulic pump failure symptoms. It covers the diagnosis process from
        initial symptom identification through root cause determination.</p>
        <p>Annotations: Blue boxes indicate measurement checkpoints with standard
        pressure ranges (20-25 MPa normal). Red diamonds represent critical
        decision points requiring operator confirmation. Green boxes represent
        successful resolution paths. All measurements should be taken at operating
        temperature with machine in neutral and engine at 1800 RPM.</p>
        <p>Source: Caterpillar 320 Service Manual, Section 4: Hydraulic System
        Diagnosis, Technical Publication No. SEBF01234, 2023 Edition,
        Page 45</p>
    </figcaption>
</figure>
```

### Example 2: Component Location Diagram
```html
<figure>
    <img src="/resources/components/main-bearing-location.png"
         title="Main Bearing Assembly Location"/>
    <figcaption>
        <p>Figure 3: Main Bearing Assembly - Component Location</p>
        <p>Depicts the location and access path for the main bearing assembly on the
        Caterpillar 320 excavator swing motor. This diagram corresponds to Step 4
        of the bearing replacement procedure and provides visual reference for component
        identification and disassembly sequencing.</p>
        <p>Annotations: ①-Cover bolts (6x M12, 90 Nm torque sequence), ②-Bearing
        housing cap, ③-Oil seal (38 mm ID, replacement required), ④-Bearing outer race.
        Component ①-④ must be removed in numbered sequence. Note: Apply thread
        locker to cover bolts (part no. 7P-1234). Allow oil to drain for at
        least 15 minutes before disassembly.</p>
        <p>Source: Caterpillar 320 Components Catalog, Section 2: Swing Drive
        Assembly, Figure 2.3, 2022 Edition</p>
    </figcaption>
</figure>
```

### Example 3: Measurement Procedure
```html
<figure>
    <img src="/resources/measurement/vibration-test-setup.png"
         title="Vibration Measurement Setup"/>
    <figcaption>
        <p>Figure 5: ISO 10816 Vibration Measurement Point Configuration</p>
        <p>Shows the accelerometer placement and measurement setup for swing motor
        bearing vibration assessment according to ISO 10816 standards. This setup
        supports the vibration diagnosis procedure in Section 3.4 of the diagnostic plan.</p>
        <p>Annotations: A-Accelerometer mounting stub (magnetic mount required),
        B-Measurement plane (axial - parallel to shaft), C-Measurement zone (bearing
        housing surface 50 mm from bearing face), T-Testing conditions (machine at
        operating temperature, normal load, stabilized speed). Collect data for 30
        seconds minimum. Acceptable values: < 4.5 mm/s RMS at 1800 RPM, > 7.0 mm/s
        RMS requires immediate shutdown.</p>
        <p>Source: ISO 10816:2018, Mechanical vibration - Measurement and
        evaluation of machine vibration, Figure B.3, Page 25</p>
    </figcaption>
</figure>
```

## Quality Assurance Checklist

### Before Including an Image, Verify:
- [ ] Image URL exists and is accessible
- [ ] Image source is on the whitelist (verified source)
- [ ] <figure> tag structure is complete and valid
- [ ] All required elements are present (figure_number, figure_name, descriptions)
- [ ] Annotations include all details from source
- [ ] Citation source is complete and accurate
- [ ] Image matches the diagnostic/repair step it supports
- [ ] Technical specifications in annotations are verified
- [ ] Purpose description explains how image aids diagnosis
- [ ] HTML structure is properly nested and closed

### Source Verification for Images:
- [ ] Source document is verified and authoritative
- [ ] Page/section reference is accurate
- [ ] Year or version of source is specified
- [ ] URL or DOI for source is provided
- [ ] Image is not fabricated or hallucinated
- [ ] All annotations match source document exactly

### Purpose Description Verification:
- [ ] Explains what image shows visually
- [ ] Identifies which text/step it corresponds to
- [ ] Describes how it aids diagnosis or repair
- [ ] Lists all technical specifications shown
- [ ] Provides context for interpretation

## Special Considerations

### Multi-Image Sequences
- Use sequential figure numbering (Figure 1, Figure 2, Figure 3...)
- Number figures in diagnostic/repair procedure order
- Cross-reference related figures in annotations (e.g., "see Figure 3 for detail")
- Maintain consistent annotation style across sequence

### Mobile-First Design
- Ensure figures are responsive and scale properly
- Test on mobile device viewports (< 768px width)
- Provide responsive captions that don't overflow
- Consider image compression for faster mobile loading

### Accessibility
- Provide meaningful alt text for screen readers
- Ensure color contrast in diagrams meets accessibility standards
- Alternative text descriptions when images are complex
- Keyboard navigable figure references when possible

### Error Prevention
If uncertain about any of the following:
- Image URL accuracy or accessibility
- Source verification status
- Annotation completeness
- Citation formatting

**DO NOT include the image**. Instead:
1. State that image information is incomplete or cannot be verified
2. Request user to provide the image or verify source
3. Proceed with text-based explanation only
4. Note the limitation in the response
